The paper deals with privacy issues in proximity services offered by geo-social networks, which involves handling sensitive location data. This makes it highly relevant to the sub-category of computer security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of location data for proximity services, which falls under the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also proposes new protocols for privacy-preserving proximity services, which involves data management and processing, making it relevant to the sub-category of databases (cs.DB) and systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper involves analysis of computation and communication costs, which is relevant to the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS).
